      "writtenOn": "2020-04-23T01:17:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1. Not on iOS (devices, at least), because it appears that there’s only a host-level ReportCrash handler, not a task-level one. On desktop macOS, there’s both a host-level ReportCrash handler and a task-level one. The task-level one is the “user” ReportCrash, and that’s the normal place exceptions are handled for user apps so that UI can be shown and so that reports go to ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports (as opposed to the same directory in the root /Library). If I remember the results of last week’s https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/2152965 experiment correctly, there was no task-level EXC_CRASH or EXC_CORPSE_NOTIFY handler on iOS (on-device) at all. You can’t see the host-level handlers unless you’re root, so I didn’t check this, but if they’re not task-level, they’d either have to be thread-level or host-level, and they wouldn’t be thread-level.\n\n2. Not in our iOS implementation, because com.apple.ReportCrash fills the EXC_CRASH or EXC_CORPSE_NOTIFY handler role, for the last-chance exception. For reasons we’ve discussed, we’re not becoming a last-chance exception handler (we can’t), we’re doing the first-chance thing. If we do the right thing here and report the first-chance exception as unhandled, it’ll continue along to the system’s host-level first-chance handler, it’ll turn into a signal, the signal will cause process death, and a last-chance exception will be raised which will go to the registered last-chance exception handler (incidentally, on the host port).",
      "revId": "df84b1a47454b4292d5b51ba3e3530b68b8e9da3",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
